nodes.body: This characteristic predicate is more restrictive in universe levels compared to concrete `TensorProduct.lift` as the argument `P` for the abstract version has to be small relative to some universe

Note we already have [IsTensorProduct](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/RingTheory/IsTensorProduct.html#IsTensorProduct), which is defined in terms of the canonical map from the explicit tensor product being an isomorphism. If you really want to characterize tensor products using a universal property, [here](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/Setting.20up.20definitions/near/272082753) are my old thoughts about the universe level restriction. What do you want to use it for?
I am just experimenting to see if I can remove  the commutative assumption and write down a characteristic predicate of tensor product over noncommutative rings.

I can prove an induction principal using this characteristic predicate
```lean
lemma IsTensorProduct.mem_closure (x : X) :
    x  AddSubgroup.closure { y |  (m : M) (n : N), y = tmul m n } := by

lemma IsTensorProduct.induction {motive : X  Prop}
    (tensor :  m n, motive (tmul m n))
    (add :  x x', motive x  motive x'  motive (x + x'))
    (neg :  x, motive x  motive (-x)) :
     x, motive x := sorry
```
These depends on `M, N` being `AddCommGroup`, but this is because I didn't figure out how to quotient `AddCommMonoid` by `AddSubmonoid`
You'd need to use AddConGen; not every `AddSubmonoid` of `AddCommMonoid` is the kernel of some AddMonoidHom (unless the monoid is cancellative, I think).
The commutativity assumption is easy to remove, but it breaks anyone who wants to take tensor products of algebras until we also fix #7152
when $R, S$ are both commutative rings and $M$ an $R$-module and $N$ an $(R, S)$-bimodule, then $M\otimes_R N$ is both an $R$-module and an $S$-module. this characteristic predicate can handle it

You may be able to prove the [AddSubmonoid.closure](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/GroupTheory/Submonoid/Basic.html#AddSubmonoid.closure) version by first showing that for any two AddCommMonoids satisfying the IsTensorProduct predicate are isomorphic (in a way compatible with the tmul), and carry out the explicit [TensorProduct](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/TensorProduct.html#TensorProduct) construction, which clearly is generated by the `tmul m n`. The only thing you need to change is [TensorProduct.Eqv.of_smul](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/TensorProduct.html#TensorProduct.Eqv), I believe.

(Because your IsTensorProduct predicate restricts to the universe of X, this only works if X doesn't live in a lower universe than M or N.)
Kevin reminded me that one can use the characteristic predicate to prove `X -> span` and `span -> X` compose to identity on `span` and `X`, so that this must be true. Thanks for your suggestion
Ah, yes. I forgot to update this string. Thanks!
